<div id="review_1638081307" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1638081307" />
    <a title="Erin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17957823-erin"><img alt="Erin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597778686p2/17957823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1638081307?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erin" href="/user/show/17957823-erin">Erin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17957823-erin?shelf=audio-books">audio-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17957823-erin?shelf=books-i-own">books-i-own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1638081307" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer122118459271115679"><b>Audio book narrated by Dan John Miller 9h 58 min</b> <br/><br/>I am over it! The whole dead wife leaving letters to her husband and trying to manage things beyond the grave like some type of master puppeteer! I often wonder if that is some strange secret desire of married female friends.<br/><br/>Update:<br/><br/>Well, I have taken two days to allow myself to mull over what worked for me and what didn&apos;t. There is no doubt that Emily Bleeker can write an emotionally charged contemporary family drama. Recently widowed, father of t</span>
  <span id="freeText122118459271115679" style="display:none"><b>Audio book narrated by Dan John Miller 9h 58 min</b> <br /><br />I am over it! The whole dead wife leaving letters to her husband and trying to manage things beyond the grave like some type of master puppeteer! I often wonder if that is some strange secret desire of married female friends.<br /><br />Update:<br /><br />Well, I have taken two days to allow myself to mull over what worked for me and what didn't. There is no doubt that Emily Bleeker can write an emotionally charged contemporary family drama. Recently widowed, father of three Luke relies on his friends and the letters of his dead wife, Natalie. But there is so much "other" going on in this story. Secrets about Natalie's life before Luke, the suspected domestic violence between Natalie's best friend, Annie and her husband Brian, Luke getting back into dating, Luke 's complicated past with his own parent. Oh and the teenage babysitter that seemed to be special to Natalie. I get that this was a technique to show how complicated we all are as human beings. We all come with our own baggage and Luke certainly has quite a bit to juggle in this book. Yet, I really didn't like him. I felt he was a jackass, but perhaps that falls with the fault of the narrator.</span>
  <a data-text-id="122118459271115679" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


