  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1522943935" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1522943935" />
    <a title="Geo (rain)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18177228-geo-rain"><img alt="Geo (rain)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1475959165p2/18177228.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1522943935?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Geo (rain)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Geo (rain)" href="/user/show/18177228-geo-rain">Geo (rain)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781503951457" href="/book/show/26209474-when-i-m-gone">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177228-geo-rain?shelf=fa">fa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177228-geo-rain?shelf=read-in-english">read-in-english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18177228-geo-rain?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1522943935" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13266833055509912183"><b>When I&apos;m Gone</b> follows Luke, returning from his wife&apos;s funeral to an empty house, finding himself alone without the woman he shared his life with for sixteen years and with the task of raising their three young children. Soon after, blue envelopes with letters handwritten by his wife, Natalie, start showing up at his house with no indication of who&apos;s sending them. She started writing them on the first day of her cancer treatment a year ago and in them she reveals aspects of her life that Luke was</span>
  <span id="freeText13266833055509912183" style="display:none"><b>When I'm Gone</b> follows Luke, returning from his wife's funeral to an empty house, finding himself alone without the woman he shared his life with for sixteen years and with the task of raising their three young children. Soon after, blue envelopes with letters handwritten by his wife, Natalie, start showing up at his house with no indication of who's sending them. She started writing them on the first day of her cancer treatment a year ago and in them she reveals aspects of her life that Luke was unaware of. And the more he reads them, the more questions begin to arise in his mind.<br /><br />I think it was well-written, with characters easy to sympathize with, and a really moving story. It focuses on a family coming to terms with the death of a loved one due to cancer, facing the hardest part: having to live without them. From Natalie's letters we also see her side, what she felt and went through while battling a disease that would ultimately take her life, and it felt honest.<br /><br />And I wished I could say I loved it, but I'd be lying. I had some issues with it, which is why I'm giving it 3 stars. I can't explain too much without giving away spoilers, but I'll say the plot at times reminded me of a soap opera, in the sense of predictability, some clichés, unnecessary drama and convenient situations. I also feel the impact Natalie's death had on their children wasn't fully explored (especially in the oldest children's case). And even if for the most part I understood Luke and his grief, I found him to be a little too willing to try to move on (too soon). <br /><br />Having said that, I'm quite happy with the ending. For me, it was satisfactory and almost made up for some of the parts I didn't like.<br /><br /><i>ARC provided by Lake Union Publishing (via NetGalley) in exchange for an honest review.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="13266833055509912183" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


